TITLE: Knex Transaction with Async/Await (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: This TypeScript example demonstrates using `knex.transaction` with `async/await`. It inserts a catalogue and then inserts books associated with that catalogue. The `await` keyword is used to ensure that each operation completes before the next one is executed. If an error occurs, the catch block handles the rollback.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/knex/blob/master/docs/src/guide/transactions.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
try {
  await knex.transaction(async (trx) => {
    const books = [
      { title: 'Canterbury Tales' },
      { title: 'Moby Dick' },
      { title: 'Hamlet' },
    ];

    const ids = await trx('catalogues').insert(
      {
        name: 'Old Books',
      },
      'id'
    );

    books.forEach((book) => (book.catalogue_id = ids[0]));
    const inserts = await trx('books').insert(books);

    console.log(inserts.length + ' new books saved.');
  });
} catch (error) {
  // If we get here, that means that neither the 'Old Books' catalogues insert,
  // nor any of the books inserts will have taken place.
  console.error(error);
}
```

