TITLE: Creating Tables with Increments (Primary Key)
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to create tables with an auto-incrementing primary key using the `increments()` method in Knex. The first example creates a simple table with `userId` as the primary key. The second shows creating a table with composite primary key ('userId', 'name') where `increments` method doesn't generate primary key.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/knex/blob/master/docs/src/guide/schema-builder.md#_snippet_24

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
// create table 'users'
// with a primary key using 'increments()'
knex.schema.createTable('users', function (table) {
  table.increments('userId');
  table.string('name');
});

// create table 'users'
// with a composite primary key ('userId', 'name').
// increments doesn't generate primary key.
knex.schema.createTable('users', function (table) {
  table.primary(['userId', 'name']);
  table.increments('userId');
  table.string('name');
});

// reference the 'users' primary key in new table 'posts'
knex.schema.createTable('posts', function (table) {
  table.integer('author').unsigned().notNullable();
  table.string('title', 30);
  table.string('content');

  table.foreign('author').references('userId').inTable('users');
});
```

